  %h2 Nuee Ardente

  %p A super heated steam with particles of lava hanging in the steam.

  %p This cloud forms at night and quietly flows down the side of the volcano.

  = illustration 'igneous_rock/nuee_ardente.jpg',
      link_to('Photocredit: Wikipedia',
              'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pyroclastic_flows_at_Mayon_Volcano.jpg')

  %p
    Many towns and villages are built at the foot of the volcano. They are at
    times directly in the path of the Nuee Ardente.

  %p
    The Nuee Ardente forms quietly at the vent of the volcano. Since the steam
    is embedded with particles of hot lava, the cloud becomes very dense. The
    density is high enough that the cloud can not rise but slides down the side
    of the volcano. As it moves through the village, and due to its great
    density, it pushes all of the air out of the village. The villagers
    suffocate.

  %p The Nuee Ardente is one of the most deadly things associated with a volcano.

  %h2 Gases Released During Volcanic Explosions
  %ol
    %li
      %strong Water:
      steam that is super heated
    %li Carbon Dioxide
    %li Sulfur Dioxide and Hydrogen Sulfide
    %li Hydrocloric Acid: HCl
    %li Hydrofluoric Acid: HF
    %li Methane: natural gas

  %p Fumaroles: small vents on the side of a volcano where gases escape.

  %p Mt. Katmai: a volcano in Alaska that produces 1,250,000 tons of HCl per year.

  %h2 Bowen's Reaction Series

  %p
    In a chamber of magma all of the minerals do not crystallize out at the same
    time. The order of crystallization is called the Bowen's Reaction Series.

  = illustration 'igneous_rock/bowens_reaction_series.png'

  %p
    Think of the magma chamber initially as being made up only of quartz. All
    the other minerals are dissolved in this quartz. As the chamber cools, its
    temperature is gradually going down. As the temperature decreases,
    different minerals solidify. Sometimes more then one mineral solidifies at
    a time. As each mineral is formed certain atoms are used up. Consequently,
    the remaining minerals must be formed out of different atoms giving the
    mineral a different composition. After all the minerals have formed, the
    chamber only has quartz in it which is the last to form. The first minerals
    to form do so at high temperatures. Quartz forms at the lowest temperature.
